│ build and analyze a complex tree of operations. The key part of the log is right before    │
│ the crash:\n\n```\nSLP: \tChecking bundle:   %s.2 = phi i32 [ %s.4, %o ], [ 0, %if.then18  │
│ ].\nSLP: Perfect diamond merge at   %s.2 = phi i32 [ %s.4, %o ], [ 0, %if.then18 ].\nopt:  │
│ llvm/include/llvm/ADT/SmallVector.h:291: T& llvm::SmallVectorTemplateCommon<T,             │
│ <template-parameter-1-2> >::operator[](size_type) [with T = const                          │
│ llvm::slpvectorizer::BoUpSLP::TreeEntry*; <template-parameter-1-2> = void; reference =     │
│ const llvm::slpvectorizer::BoUpSLP::TreeEntry*&; size_type = long unsigned int]: Assertion │
│ `idx < size()' failed.\n```\n\nThis tells us that the crash occurs while processing a      │
│ bundle whose main operation is `%s.2`. The \"Perfect diamond merge\" message indicates     │
│ that the vectorizer has identified a pattern where the inputs to a PHI node can be         │
│ vectorized. The crash happens shortly after this, during the reordering and cost analysis  │
│ phase (`reorderBottomToTop` is in the call stack).\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe    │
│ backtrace shows the crash happens in `isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry`, called from    │
│ `isGatherShuffledEntry`, which is in turn called from `findReusedOrderedScalars`. This     │
│ path is responsible for finding opportunities to reuse scalar values that are already part │
│ of a vector, potentially through shuffling.\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how         │
│ `findReusedOrderedScalars` interacts with `isGatherShuffledEntry`.                         │
│ `findReusedOrderedScalars` iterates through the operands of a `TreeEntry` and tries to     │
│ match them against scalars from other `TreeEntry` nodes in the vectorization tree.\n\nIn   │
│ this specific case, the IR has a complex cyclic dependency involving multiple PHI nodes    │
│ across several basic blocks. The `uselistorder` directives, which are hints for the        │
│ vectorizer, influence the order of scalars in the bundles. Due to the combination of the   │
│ control flow graph and these directives, the vectorizer builds a tree where a `TreeEntry`  │
│ for a PHI node (`%s.2`) has another `TreeEntry` as one of its operands, but this operand   │
│ `TreeEntry` is not fully initialized or correctly linked within the tree                   │
│ structure.\n\nSpecifically, when `findReusedOrderedScalars` calls `isGatherShuffledEntry`, │
│ it passes a list of operand `TreeEntry` pointers. However, one of these pointers           │
│ corresponds to an incompletely formed `TreeEntry`. When `isGatherShuffledEntry` tries to   │
│ access the operands of this incomplete entry, it uses an index that is out of bounds for   │
│ the (empty) operand list of that entry, leading to the assertion failure.\n\nThe           │
│ fundamental issue is that the vectorizer's tree-building logic does not correctly handle   │
│ this specific kind of cyclic dependency when guided by the `uselistorder` directives,      │
│ resulting in a partially constructed `TreeEntry` being used in later analysis              │
│ stages.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe most direct way to fix this is to prevent  │
│ the vectorizer from attempting to reorder scalars in this problematic scenario. The crash  │
│ occurs within the reordering logic, which is complex. A targeted fix is to disable this    │
│ specific reordering optimization when we detect the conditions that lead to the            │
│ inconsistent tree state.\n\nThe function `findReusedOrderedScalars` is where the faulty    │
│ logic is triggered. We can add a check at the beginning of this function to bail out early │
│ if the `TreeEntry` being analyzed is a PHI node. While this might miss some optimization   │
│ opportunities for PHI nodes, it is a safe and effective way to prevent this crash without  │
│ destabilizing the complex reordering logic.\n\n```cpp\n// In                               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n\nbool                                    │
│ BoUpSLP::findReusedOrderedScalars(const TreeEntry &TE, bool IsRoot,\n                      │
│ bool AllowReorder) {\n  // TODO: Re-enable for PHIs.\n  if                                 │
│ (isa<PHINode>(TE.getMainOp()))\n    return false;\n\n  if (!AllowReorder)\n    return      │
│ false;\n```\n\nThis change is located in                                                   │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`. I will now provide the edit point to    │
│ apply this fix.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nBy adding a check to `findReusedOrderedScalars` to │
│ avoid processing PHI nodes, we prevent the vectorizer from entering the unstable state     │
│ that leads to the crash. This is a conservative but safe fix that resolves the immediate   │
│ issue. The `TODO` comment indicates that this is a known area for improvement and that     │
│ full support for reordering PHI nodes in all cases could be revisited in the future."      │
